                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Nicely written, I thought.  Gives too much credit to the players for complaining, though.  I feel it is obvious that the only problem Sony has realized is that the exodus of players to other games (all of them, I think WoW gets too much credit by itself) is starting to affect thier bottom line, so now they suddenly care.  They aren't listening to us players, they are listening to thier accountants.  Still, if it gets the players goals accomplished, who really cares why.
<br />

<br />
I never really blamed Sony for ignoring the players.  They are a business, by definition they want to make the largest profit possible.  Why do people act so shocked when Sony tries to do just that?  I mean, if you ran a business that would get the same level of sales whether or not you offered customer service and quality products, would you bother?  I know I wouldn't.  Everything they get away with comes at your consent when you willingly give your credit info over to them each month.
<br />

<br />
Incidentally, this is probably why Sony caters to the "uber" players.  The average player will keep paying anyway, but when the uber player runs out of content, he will quit.  Again, if the average players would start voting with thier wallet, maybe Sony would take notice (which, hopefully, is just the case right now).
<br />

<br />
And finally, when you say you quit, citing Sony as treating you bad, then you gloat about how Sony is not getting your $13 a month, don't Ebay.  It defeats the purpose.  Sony doesn't care whose $13 they get, as long as they get it.....</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Amerie Robeseeker, 65th level Enchantress
