                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">This article is a nicely written set of fabrications.  The idiotic proposals would ruin the game.  This is propaganda from a loudmouth, and I'm ashamed to see it reposted here.
<br />

<br />
Contention: It's all Sony's fault for rushing things and that the Verant/989  was in some way better.
<br />

<br />
Reality:  Everquest has always been rushed, from Day 1 to today.  Does any one remember that the Original Release's audio system only worked on two cards and was utterly replaced three weeks in?  Does anyone remember the Velious Graphics disaster?  Does anyone remember Luclin's busted zones?  LDoN and Ykesha were fairly bug-free releases.  GoD wasn't bad except for the unfinished high end zones.  The real track record is that Sony has done better than Verant ever did.  The one exception was losing thier minds on the DX9 thing.
<br />

<br />
Contention:  EQ was never meant to be a raid game.
<br />

<br />
Reality: Of course it was.  The idea of large bands doing things together is a core value from the get-go.  The original designers expected guilds to fight through the Fire Giants and kill Nagafen.  What nobody realized was that servers would hit populations of 3000+ (in beta, 1000 was a dream) and have ten 100 player leveled-out guilds.  That made raiding inevitable, on a scale that the original and Kunark content didn't support. So Verant listened to our bored complaints, and added content to suit us.  It worked, and it continues to work for much of the player base.
<br />

<br />
Contention: That quests and tradeskills were ever more than a sideline in EQ.  
<br />

<br />
Reality: While there are a ton of quests, few of them up until Velious resulted in any major rewards.  Rewards came from camping Lower Guk or Sol B in classic EQ.  Questing and tradeskiling were always a sideline, and being a mass murderer is the major point of the game.  Get over it, or go play DAOC.
<br />

<br />
Contention: That the 'story' of early everquest was any better than what is in GoD.
<br />

<br />
Reality: The 'Story' of Early EQ is a mess of incomplete quests, nonsensical societies, and out of place NPCs.  Some attempt was made mid-Kunark to fix some of these, but many storylines lie fallow or broken.  Whole regions of the world from release were left out.  Now if you are actually paying attention in GoD, there is a wonderful story connected together by a massive quest that can be done mostly by small groups.  And it's not right there in your face--you have to dig for it, and work your faction, and do things beyond just killing the biggest and baddest in every zone.  There are bits there for less powerful guilds, and a progress path for those guilds to become stronger by doing the quest work.  GoD doesn't suck half as much as the bandwagon says it does, if you go there prepared for something more than a PoK freeride.
<br />

<br />
Contention: That there was some past day that the developers listened, and that 'today' they have grown out of touch.
<br />

<br />
Reality: Anyone who has a memory can tell you that Customer Service is  better than it has EVER been.  How easily we forget the days when you would get a year suspension just for telling Verant that someone had hacked your account.  How nice it is now that you can get item reimbursal for verified game bugs, when once you would have been told 'Tough Luck on that NPC eating your Fiery Avenger'.  The utter lack of records makes it hard to remember those first 7 months of EQ when 989 held the entire community in suspense on what random thing they would change next.  I remember mass disbanding of guilds for 'exploits' without investigation--it happened on my server.  Who here remembers the instant nerfing of ANYTHING that could give player advantage?  What of the 'It's not broken' defense against any number of obvious game bugs?  Nowadays we have patch messages that show things being fixed, producer letters, responses from the tradeskill guys at eqtraders, responses from the spellguy here, and actual responses from Smed now and again.
<br />

<br />
Let's examine this man's solutions one by one:
<br />

<br />
FIX THE BUGS and STOP IGNORING YOUR CUSTOMERS 
<br />

<br />
Fix the bugs is good.  What SOE's programmers did to the game in March was inexcusable.  But that's a thing in itself, not an overall customer complaint.  Every week we get some fixes to minor things.
<br />

<br />
What the customers asked for was more content.  The #1 request prior to GoD was 'More level 65 zones please'.  So Sony gave us an infinitude of instanced zones with GoD.  And to be honest, they aren't bad ones.  There is lots to do in GoD, and its pretty well balanced right now.  So stop crying and go play in the sewers.
<br />

<br />
POPULATE OLD UNUSED ZONES WITH NEW CONTENT
<br />

<br />
Consistency is a virtue.  On the one hand this guy wants to preserve lore and on the other hand he wants to destroy the old lore.  I'd say that what he wants is zones that he has used up to be useful to him out of nostalgia.  Revamping old content is probably the lowest priority of anything against the current problems.  There's already a ton of 'factional intrigue' on Antonica, and nobody's using it.  The beauty of EQ's design is that new zones can be added anywhere, and suddenly Southwest Freeport could spring up if there was need to do so.  There isn't.
<br />

<br />
STOP PANDERING TO UBERGUILDS and FOCUS ON CONTENT FOR NORMAL PEOPLE 
<br />

<br />
As far as I can see, the uberguilds are the ones who got the broken, useless content in GoD and LDoN.  The zones there for the rest of us worked well and had nice toys.  And GoD got rebalanced recently for the less uber.  So, umm, I think someone needs to read fewer FOH web pages and pay more attention to what is going on in patch messages and Ferubi.  There's a lively community playing in the first 5 GoD zones today.
<br />

<br />
Good point about the gear gap.  Of course, those Type 7 25 hp 25 mana augments that drop all over the open GoD zones from one day spawning, one groupable mobs go a long way towards fixing that.
<br />

<br />
HIRE MORE DEVS, QA and GAMEMASTERS
<br />

<br />
QA is only as good as the test plans and programmers driving it.  I think we've seen in the last two months that awareness isn't the issue.  They need to hire some good labor to fix the graphics engine, not more adminstrative personnel.
<br />

<br />
Petition answering seems pretty quick right now.  There's somebody running 3 GM quests a week on my server, too.
<br />

<br />
MAKE EVERQUEST FUN AGAIN
<br />

<br />
Everquest is quite fun right now, barring game destroying graphics bugs.  There's more to do, and more ways to do it than ever before.  Unless you are stuck at the endgame, you shouldn't be bored.  Nevertheless, some people use games up and need to move on.  More power to ya, guys.
<br />

<br />
I feel as much nostalgia towards the way that EQ 'used to be' as anyone.  On the other hand, I feel an equal amount of hatred towards how messed up EQ used to be.  Everquest has only gotten better as a game over the last year.  It's broadened, and its deepened, and it offers more to every level of player.  Like it's always been, though, it's up to each player to make his own adventure in that context.
<br />

<br />
One point from another post: 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">A couple of issues with this post - Luclin has EXCELLENT lore. It's not easy to find, but the storylines are fabulous.</span>
<br />

<br />
While there is great potential, Luclin's lore is unimplemented and contradictory beyond Shadowhaven.  There's supposed to be this big war between Katta and Seru, yet there are no soldiers and no conflict.  Everybody in Katta is Vampyre focused, but the Vampyres themselves are scattered and have hardly any plot of thier own.  None of the NPCs care about the three way war between the owlbears, grimlings, and sonic wolves that's happening on thier doorstep.  Acrylia Caverns is a big WTF? The cat people don't fit, the akhevans don't fit, and the Grieg story is unfinished. The snakes fit, but there's no way to look at thier culture from the inside--a terrible omission IMHO.  I feel like Luclin had the best potential for being the best expansion, but it got ruined by being too big to ever finish.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
